WEBVTT

00:00.162 --> 00:06.168
So Burnett and I had a great week along with Pastor Britt and Gayle and some other friends.

00:06.268 --> 00:09.831
We went out to the lighthouse and spent the week out there.

00:09.851 --> 00:12.293
And that was a really great time.

00:13.575 --> 00:15.116
So thanks for letting us get some time away.

00:15.156 --> 00:19.921
Thanks for Pastor Lance taking care of preaching last week.

00:19.941 --> 00:22.363
But it was just a really, really wonderful time getting away.

00:22.403 --> 00:27.087
The first time we ever went out there was with our kids.

00:27.208 --> 00:29.810
So our oldest son is,

00:29.922 --> 00:30.162
28?

00:31.805 --> 00:32.386
Our youngest.

00:32.406 --> 00:34.008
28, see?

00:34.689 --> 00:36.952
I got that right.

00:37.032 --> 00:38.815
He had his third birthday at the lighthouse.

00:38.875 --> 00:41.138
Back then, they would let you take really young kids out.

00:41.899 --> 00:44.743
I think now you have to be like seven or nine or something for going out.

00:45.184 --> 00:46.946
But that was a long time ago.

00:46.986 --> 00:50.211
And back then, of course, you had to take long storybooks to read the kids at night.

00:50.772 --> 00:57.842
And one of the books that we always enjoyed with our kids, and maybe you know this one, is cloudy with a chance of meatballs.

00:58.754 --> 01:05.381
It's the folks that live in the town of Chuan Swallow, and it turns out that all the weather fronts in the town of Chuan Swallow are food.

01:06.061 --> 01:10.826
And so it will like hail pancakes and rain syrup in the morning for breakfast.

01:11.426 --> 01:19.454
And it goes on to the day, and then they run into some extreme weather events that eventually make the town uninhabitable because of the giant pancakes that are landing on them.

01:19.835 --> 01:22.237
So that was cloudy with a chance of meatballs.

01:23.719 --> 01:27.282
We have been working our way through the story of the children of Israel.

01:27.522 --> 01:37.292
and their journey from slavery in Egypt to the promised land and kind of making parallels between that and our journey as followers of Jesus as we move through this life.

01:37.993 --> 01:51.828
And I think scripture uses those parallels often that we have been brought out of a place of slavery and that we are now on a journey with Jesus and ahead of us is the promised land in eternal home with Jesus.

01:52.409 --> 01:57.394
And so we've been looking at various episodes along the journey that Israel had.

01:57.826 --> 02:00.350
I've been encouraging you to keep a travel log.

02:00.610 --> 02:02.794
What I mean by that is, do some journaling.

02:03.334 --> 02:07.401
Read the story on your own and prayerfully say, Lord, how do I learn?

02:07.921 --> 02:08.623
How do I learn?

02:08.683 --> 02:10.806
How do I gain something from this from my own life?

02:10.926 --> 02:11.968
I hope you're doing that.

02:13.069 --> 02:20.080
The story I want to talk about today is kind of the Israelite version of Cloudy with the Chance of Meatballs.

02:20.961 --> 02:23.986
We're going to talk about the miracle of manna today.

02:24.450 --> 02:30.016
and how Israel was provided for in the wilderness with literally food from heaven.

02:31.177 --> 02:35.702
To give you some context, at this point Israel is about a month and a half into their journey.

02:36.463 --> 02:43.170
And what has led them up to this journey first was their cry for deliverance from slavery in Egypt.

02:43.190 --> 02:45.513
They had been crying out for that.

02:45.953 --> 02:47.775
And then they saw how God provided.

02:48.396 --> 02:54.322
He sent Moses, and of course there were those 10 terrible plagues that fell on Egypt that finally

02:54.466 --> 02:56.108
forced Pharaoh's hand to let them go.

02:56.148 --> 03:02.418
Then they witnessed that God led them by this fiery cloud.

03:02.438 --> 03:08.366
We talked about that and the imagery there of, we see God's Holy Spirit leading and guiding in our lives.

03:08.947 --> 03:16.017
There was this visible manifestation that God's power was with them, that he was the one who was leading them in the way that they should go.

03:16.037 --> 03:19.282
No sooner had that journey started.

03:19.490 --> 03:26.001
then they found themselves trapped between the Red Sea and Pharaoh's pursuing army, seemingly with no way out.

03:27.043 --> 03:39.483
Turns out that Pharaoh, having let them go, had kind of a buyer's remorse, or maybe we should say an emancipator's remorse, as he saw he had just released his entire workforce.

03:40.205 --> 03:45.874
And so the people cry out to Moses and they say, why did you bring us out here to die?

03:46.306 --> 03:49.850
because death seems certain with Pharaoh's army closing in.

03:49.930 --> 03:54.195
But then, as we talked about, they are miraculously delivered.

03:54.636 --> 03:57.299
God parts the waters and lets them pass through.

03:57.319 --> 04:04.127
The last week, Pastor Lance preached on one of their first water stops in that desert journey.

04:05.128 --> 04:08.932
One that turned out initially to be deeply disappointing because the water was bitter.

04:09.032 --> 04:10.134
It was undrinkable.

04:10.915 --> 04:13.778
And the people again cried out to Moses and they said,

04:13.890 --> 04:15.492
Why did you bring us here to die?

04:15.512 --> 04:17.855
This is a recurring theme in their lives.

04:17.875 --> 04:20.479
Whenever something goes wrong, they're pretty sure they're going to die.

04:21.760 --> 04:27.869
But once again, God provided that miracle that rendered the bitter water sweet and drinkable.

04:28.990 --> 04:34.618
So now we're finding them traveling on from that oasis, but they are running low on supplies.

04:35.739 --> 04:38.002
Do you want to guess what their response is?

04:39.682 --> 04:42.885
They cry out to Moses and they say, why did you bring this out here to die?

04:43.085 --> 04:48.991
This is just their response to everything, which I think is the textbook definition of being a slow learner.

04:49.771 --> 04:52.974
And yet despite their grumbling, God once again provides.

04:53.015 --> 04:54.256
And so we're gonna pick it up there.

04:54.296 --> 04:57.499
This is Exodus chapter 16, verses four and five.

04:59.421 --> 05:09.490
Then the Lord said to Moses, behold, I'm about to reign bread from heaven for you and the people should go out and gather a day's portion every day that I may test them.

05:09.954 --> 05:12.057
whether they will walk in my law or not.

05:12.918 --> 05:19.025
On the sixth day, when they prepare what they bring in, it will be twice as much as they gather daily.

05:19.045 --> 05:25.874
Now I'm gonna say at the outset that there was more provided for them than just this miracle bread.

05:26.514 --> 05:27.676
There's also quail.

05:27.936 --> 05:31.380
Each evening quail appeared, each morning the miracle bread appeared.

05:32.101 --> 05:35.245
I wanna focus this morning just on the bread aspect of this.

05:36.206 --> 05:39.090
I think it is maybe the harder of the two to understand,

05:39.362 --> 05:43.366
And there were some very specific instructions given concerning it.

05:44.167 --> 05:48.351
We're also going to see how it plays a significant role in later biblical history.

05:49.272 --> 05:52.074
So what was this bread from heaven?

05:53.155 --> 05:57.560
That is exactly the question that the people of Israel had when they first laid eyes on it.

05:58.981 --> 06:03.265
When the people of Israel sought, they said to one another, what is it?

06:04.306 --> 06:08.210
In fact, the name that they gave it is the Hebrew word man.

06:08.674 --> 06:12.679
It wasn't called manna until it was translated into Greek.

06:13.100 --> 06:22.332
Turns out that in Greek, the Greeks don't like words that end on consonants, so they added an A, and our English translations went ahead and just kept that.

06:22.412 --> 06:30.583
So we get the word manna from this Hebrew word, man, and literally what the Hebrew translates to is, what is it?

06:31.544 --> 06:34.468
That was the name they gave it, right?

06:34.488 --> 06:36.050
Here's how it is described.

06:37.602 --> 06:46.574
In the morning, do lay around the camp, and when the do had gone up, there was, on the face of the wilderness, a fine flake-like thing, fine as frost on the ground.

06:47.335 --> 06:53.283
It was like coriander seed, white, and the taste of it was like wafers made with honey.

06:54.204 --> 06:59.711
So it was a small frost-like flake with a sweet taste.

06:59.831 --> 07:02.034
I thought about this, and you know what it was?

07:08.354 --> 07:09.355
Tell me I'm not right.

07:12.880 --> 07:13.300
All right.

07:13.801 --> 07:16.264
So they get frosted flakes every morning for breakfast.

07:16.845 --> 07:29.681
Now, what is more significant than the shape or the taste is the deeper test and lesson that was embedded within that miracle breakfast cereal, if you will.

07:30.582 --> 07:36.530
Right off the top, the Lord tells Moses that there is a test embedded in this manna.

07:38.018 --> 07:49.294
The Lord said to Moses, behold, I'm about to reign bread from heaven for you and the people should go out and gather a day's portion every day, that I may test them whether they will walk in my law or not.

07:50.396 --> 07:54.361
Now as you read on about manna, you find out that there were rules attached to it.

07:54.922 --> 07:57.586
There were some laws about the collecting of manna.

07:58.367 --> 08:06.098
The Lord says that how the people respond to those rules is going to reveal something about the motivations and the priorities of their heart.

08:06.850 --> 08:10.175
I think that is what God often is doing with his law.

08:10.235 --> 08:14.862
It's not so much about the law as it is revealing the things that are deep in our hearts.

08:15.303 --> 08:18.167
And our response to God reveals those things.

08:18.668 --> 08:19.589
So what were the rules?

08:19.649 --> 08:23.795
Well, the first rule was that they were to collect just what they needed for today.

08:24.156 --> 08:25.558
This from Exodus 16.

08:26.740 --> 08:36.274
Here's what the Lord's commanded, gather of it, each one of you, as much as he can eat, you shall take an omer according to the number of persons that each of you has in his tent.

08:36.642 --> 08:40.929
So they have this kind of set amount in Omer that they click for each person.

08:40.969 --> 08:44.615
And so maybe you're wondering, well, what is an Omer?

08:45.035 --> 08:48.280
Now I had an uncle, Emma, but I think that's different.

08:48.881 --> 08:52.968
So exit of 1636 actually tells us what an Omer is.

08:53.448 --> 08:55.632
It says an Omer is the 10th part of an EFA.

08:55.912 --> 08:57.254
So that clears that up.

09:00.419 --> 09:04.626
OK. Best as we can tell, an Omer equals about two quarts.

09:04.770 --> 09:07.953
So they were told to collect about two quarts per day.

09:08.854 --> 09:13.079
Also they were told that there would be no leftovers and no hoarding.

09:14.020 --> 09:19.145
Exodus 16, 19 Moses said to them, let no one leave any of it over till the morning.

09:19.745 --> 09:23.449
So you collect it every day and you are to use what you've collected.

09:23.489 --> 09:25.612
You're not supposed to try and keep the leftovers.

09:25.632 --> 09:27.674
You're not to try and build up a stockpile of it.

09:28.695 --> 09:31.858
Except there was one exception to this and that was on the Sabbath.

09:32.642 --> 09:43.979
On the sixth day, so the day before the Sabbath, they gathered twice as much bread to Omer's each, and when all the leaders of the congregation came and told Moses, he said to them, this is what the Lord has commanded.

09:44.500 --> 09:54.956
Tomorrow is a day of solemn rest, a holy Sabbath to the Lord, bake which you will bake and boil which you will boil, and all that is left over lay aside to be kept until morning.

09:55.857 --> 10:01.906
So the only day that you could collect more than one day's supply was on the day before the Sabbath.

10:02.146 --> 10:04.769
That was to allow you to rest.

10:05.490 --> 10:16.342
There was this principle established from the time of creation of setting aside a regular time, a weekly time for rest, for contentment, for quietness.

10:16.882 --> 10:23.069
And even in the giving of this miracle bread, the manna, God said, I still want you to have this day of rest.

10:24.130 --> 10:26.773
Now there were some extra miracles attached to the manna.

10:28.595 --> 10:31.058
This from Exodus 16, verses 17 and 18.

10:31.170 --> 10:36.177
which tells us that everybody got an omer regardless of their gathering ability.

10:36.417 --> 10:37.058
Take a look at this.

10:37.759 --> 10:49.315
They gathered some more, some less, but when they measured it with an omer, whoever gathered much had nothing left over and whoever gathered little had no lack.

10:49.836 --> 10:50.557
Isn't that interesting?

10:51.578 --> 10:54.162
Now I don't think that means that laziness was rewarded.

10:54.562 --> 11:01.073
Okay, this isn't the idea that the guy who's lazy and just doesn't want to go out and do anything, he still ends up with just as much as the guy who is working really hard.

11:01.694 --> 11:08.566
I think really what it's saying is that both the weak and the strong, the young and the aged, were cared for equally.

11:09.687 --> 11:20.786
And so the elderly person that maybe can't collect as much at the end of the day finds that they have as much as the young who were in good strength and could collect a lot.

11:21.506 --> 11:27.513
So both the weak and the strong were equally cared for by God in collecting the manum.

11:28.954 --> 11:37.043
Now there were people who tried to cheat the system as they're always are, and what they discovered if they did that is that they were stinkers and winners.

11:38.325 --> 11:41.969
Moses said to them, let no one leave any of it over till the morning.

11:43.010 --> 11:49.597
Some left part of it till the morning, and it bred worms and stink.

11:49.617 --> 11:50.098
So,

11:50.178 --> 11:52.140
Cheaters never win, right?

11:53.762 --> 11:57.327
But again, they were allowed to double up on Fridays, right?

11:57.427 --> 11:59.189
On the sixth day, they gathered twice as much.

11:59.670 --> 12:07.479
Moses said to them, tomorrow's the day of solemn rest, all this leftover lay aside to be kept to mourning, and it did not stink, and there were no worms in it.

12:08.000 --> 12:12.045
So if any other time during the week, you try to hold on to it, it's not gonna go well.

12:12.565 --> 12:16.530
But the day before the Sabbath, you were allowed to collect twice as much.

12:18.018 --> 12:23.704
Remember, God told Moses the outset that there was a test embedded in this gift of manna.

12:24.686 --> 12:27.769
And the test was to see if the people would obey God's words.

12:27.789 --> 12:29.090
So how did they do?

12:29.151 --> 12:37.120
Well, we already know that there are quite a few folks who apparently tried to hoard the leftovers and they stink literally.

12:38.081 --> 12:40.263
How about that double collection on the Sabbath?

12:41.504 --> 12:46.450
Well, on seventh day, some of the people went out to gather, but they found none.

12:47.170 --> 12:52.215
And the Lord said to Moses, how long will you refuse to keep my commandments and my laws?

12:53.637 --> 12:57.100
These folks out there, you know, that didn't save anything the day before.

12:57.881 --> 13:01.325
Or maybe they thought they could hoard even more of it on the Sabbath day.

13:01.885 --> 13:04.027
He says, don't you people listen?

13:04.708 --> 13:06.230
Didn't you hear what I told you?

13:06.270 --> 13:09.914
There could be a couple reasons that folks were out hunting on the Sabbath.

13:10.034 --> 13:14.258
Maybe they had failed to take advantage of the double portion the day before.

13:14.626 --> 13:18.091
You know, every other day collecting extra had been a bad thing.

13:18.111 --> 13:26.504
And so maybe despite they've been instructed, they just didn't believe there would actually be any different on Friday than it had been on Thursday.

13:26.564 --> 13:33.074
Or maybe they had collected the double provision, but they were still back hoping to grab even more.

13:34.556 --> 13:37.400
Either way, they weren't being obedient to what the Lord had told them.

13:38.322 --> 13:41.106
It was either unbelief or it was greed.

13:42.626 --> 13:44.969
So what is there for us to learn from manna?

13:46.651 --> 13:56.024
Well, probably the most profound, well, yes, the most profound New Testament connection that was made to this story of manna was made by Jesus himself.

13:56.945 --> 14:02.733
And it occurs in the aftermath of another miracle bread encounter.

14:03.194 --> 14:04.275
Maybe you remember the story.

14:04.295 --> 14:06.258
In John 6, we have the account

14:06.466 --> 14:18.399
of Jesus feeding 5,000 people by blessing and breaking five small biscuits and a couple of small fish that had been donated out of a young boy's lunch.

14:18.419 --> 14:28.851
And besides having their tummies filled, the crowd is exuberant because they see this miracle as proof positive that Jesus is the great prophet that has been long prophesied.

14:29.712 --> 14:31.474
They are thrilled

14:31.554 --> 14:39.666
to see their ancient prophecies being fulfilled and to say, this is the man who can care for us, who can meet our every need.

14:39.747 --> 14:48.981
Because just think if he can do that with one little boy's lunch, just imagine the power he has to make all of our dreams come true.

14:51.284 --> 14:54.890
John tells us that Jesus actually had to remove himself from the crowd.

14:55.971 --> 15:00.338
He says that he went and he hit himself away from them to avoid

15:00.578 --> 15:03.762
them trying to forcibly make him a king.

15:05.545 --> 15:07.788
By the next morning, Jesus actually left the area.

15:07.848 --> 15:09.270
He crossed the Sea of Galilee.

15:10.331 --> 15:15.699
But as any camera shy celebrity can tell you, the fans will eventually find you.

15:16.680 --> 15:23.409
And the people still excited, riled up, wanting to lay hands on this miracle worker and make him their king.

15:23.810 --> 15:26.574
Sure enough, they finally find where he is gone.

15:27.475 --> 15:29.618
And here is what he says to them.

15:31.778 --> 15:33.541
Jesus replied, I tell you the truth.

15:34.562 --> 15:36.445
You want to be with me because I fed you.

15:37.507 --> 15:40.472
Not because you understood the miraculous signs.

15:40.952 --> 15:41.754
See, that's important.

15:41.794 --> 15:45.980
He's saying to them, what I did yesterday was not just about a free lunch.

15:46.862 --> 15:54.413
What I did yesterday was a sign that should have pointed you to something greater that's happening, but you're not paying attention to the signs.

15:55.315 --> 15:59.922
The reason you're here, the reason you're so excited is not because of great spiritual insight,

16:00.322 --> 16:02.104
is because you want more free lunch.

16:03.645 --> 16:06.849
But don't be so concerned about perishable things like food.

16:08.010 --> 16:12.455
Spend your energy seeking the eternal life that the Son of Man can give you.

16:13.436 --> 16:16.859
For God the Father has given me the seal of His approval.

16:17.980 --> 16:20.963
Saying, the sign here isn't about the bread.

16:21.023 --> 16:23.466
It's about who I am.

16:23.526 --> 16:25.268
That's what you need to understand.

16:26.509 --> 16:27.410
They replied,

16:27.714 --> 16:29.296
We want to perform God's works too.

16:29.336 --> 16:30.137
