18:06.455 --> 18:13.064
So the fact that Jesus and the Jewish rabbi would even have a conversation with this woman was, went side of all the cultural norms.

18:14.486 --> 18:18.031
But the conversation he had with her was not about bread, it was about water.

18:18.692 --> 18:20.114
And here's what Jesus said.

18:20.962 --> 18:26.209
Jesus worried as he was from his journey was sitting beside the well, a woman from Samaria came to draw water.

18:26.449 --> 18:27.891
Jesus said to her, give me a drink.

18:28.712 --> 18:34.339
The Samaritan woman said to him, how was it that you and Jew asked for a drink for me, a woman of Samaria?

18:34.940 --> 18:37.263
For Jews have no dealings with Samaritans.

18:38.785 --> 18:49.138
Jesus answered her, if you knew the gift of God and who it is that is saying to you, give me a drink, you would have asked Him and He would have given you living water.

18:50.210 --> 18:53.934
Jesus said to her, everyone who drinks of this water will be thirsty again.

18:53.974 --> 18:58.838
But whoever drinks of the water that I will give him will never be thirsty again.

18:58.878 --> 19:05.645
The water that I will give him will become in him a spring of water welling up to eternal life.

19:07.006 --> 19:12.111
Obviously, Jesus is talking about something more than just physical desires.

19:12.992 --> 19:19.538
He's saying there's something even deeper in the human being than hunger and thirst.

19:19.810 --> 19:21.031
for bread and water.

